WEBVTT

00:11.714 --> 00:13.236
Hey church, I hope you're doing well.

00:13.696 --> 00:20.665
These are disorienting times, but we gather together on Sundays, even if digitally, to recenter our hearts on God.

00:20.945 --> 00:22.106
And that's what we're gonna do now.

00:22.747 --> 00:26.732
If you've got a Bible, go ahead and grab it, open up to the book of Philippians.

00:27.413 --> 00:32.178
And while you turn there, I wanna take a minute to take up our offering.

00:32.279 --> 00:36.063
If you're not a part of our church, then don't worry about giving.

00:36.103 --> 00:38.546
This is something that we do as a family.

00:38.658 --> 00:47.151
But for those of you who are a part of our church, this is a way that we pool our resources together to be able to serve one another and to love our city.

00:47.712 --> 00:49.394
And so we do that every week.

00:49.434 --> 00:55.503
We want to be a generous people because we serve a generous God and there are so many needs right now.

00:56.064 --> 00:59.590
And so if you want to give, you can do that through push pay.

00:59.610 --> 01:00.832
It's an app that you download.

01:00.852 --> 01:07.762
You can get it at the app store on your smartphone and just search reality LA in there and we will give

01:07.874 --> 01:13.660
joyfully and sacrificially, and we will trust the Lord to do a great work with all of that.

01:14.461 --> 01:19.547
Okay, so I'm going to be preaching on Philippians chapter 1, verses 3 through 11.

01:20.027 --> 01:25.593
We started a new series last week in the book of Philippians that we are calling defiant joy.

01:25.653 --> 01:33.142
This is a difficult, strange time, but we refuse to let our joy be determined by our circumstances.

01:33.702 --> 01:37.106
And so today we're going to be talking about unexpected

01:37.282 --> 01:38.123
gratitude.

01:38.684 --> 01:44.814
And so I'm going to be reading Philippians 1 verses 3 through 11 and then I'll open our time with a word of prayer.

01:46.036 --> 01:48.840
Philippians chapter 1 verses 3 through 11.

01:50.883 --> 02:03.283
I thank my God and all my remembrance of you always in every prayer of mine for you all making my prayer with joy because of your partnership in the gospel from the first day until now.

02:04.104 --> 02:05.426
And I am sure of this

02:05.858 --> 02:11.026
that he who began a good work in you will bring it to completion at the day of Jesus Christ.

02:11.968 --> 02:15.934
It is right for me to feel this way about you all because I hold you in my heart.

02:16.675 --> 02:24.448
For you are all partakers with me of grace, both in my imprisonment and in the defense and confirmation of the gospel.

02:25.289 --> 02:26.331
For God is my witness.

02:26.852 --> 02:30.738
How I yearn for you all with the affection of Christ Jesus.

02:31.234 --> 02:50.058
And it is my prayer that your love may abound more and more with knowledge and all discernment so that you may approve what is excellent and so be pure and blameless for the day of Christ filled with the fruit of righteousness that comes through Jesus Christ to the glory and praise of God.

02:51.259 --> 02:52.080
This is God's word.

02:52.120 --> 02:53.522
Let's pray together.

02:55.810 --> 03:03.500
God, we come before you needing your grace to intervene and bring change in our hearts and in our lives.

03:04.461 --> 03:05.963
We thank you for your word.

03:06.023 --> 03:22.564
And God, we pray today through the preaching of your word that you would give us perspective, that you would give us direction, and that you would fill us with courage to keep going, to keep following Christ in the midst of a difficult time in all of this pandemic.

03:22.604 --> 03:23.986
Lord, we just look to you.

03:24.834 --> 03:38.591
And we continue to cry out on behalf of our city, Lord, for those who are sick, for those who are grieving loss, for those who have lost work and are struggling with needing financial provision.

03:38.651 --> 03:45.419
God, we look to you as our hope in a time where things that we've placed our hope in have been stripped away.

03:45.499 --> 03:51.647
We look to you and we look to you with faith, with expectancy, believing that you are at work in all of this.

03:52.208 --> 03:54.130
We pray this all in Jesus' name.

03:54.434 --> 03:54.855
Amen.

03:56.777 --> 03:56.978
All right.

03:56.998 --> 03:59.080
Well, today we're talking about gratitude.

03:59.140 --> 04:04.388
And you might hear that and think, how can we talk about gratitude in the middle of a pandemic?

04:04.728 --> 04:10.076
How insensitive, come on, people are suffering and struggling and you want to talk about gratitude?

04:11.077 --> 04:13.540
Well, you could put the same question to the Apostle Paul.

04:14.081 --> 04:14.922
He was in prison.

04:15.002 --> 04:16.184
You're suffering greatly.

04:16.204 --> 04:22.152
He's literally awaiting his death and he's writing a letter to a church that is experiencing persecution.

04:22.212 --> 04:23.474
And yet,

04:23.906 --> 04:29.093
The very first words that come out of his mouth after the greeting in this letter to the Philippians is this.

04:29.814 --> 04:31.497
I thank my God.

04:32.598 --> 04:35.923
How can Paul talk about gratitude and the time of adversity?

04:36.664 --> 04:39.728
Why would we talk about gratitude and a time of suffering?

04:40.709 --> 04:43.814
Because it's the kind of gratitude that transcends our circumstances.

04:44.434 --> 04:48.540
It's the kind of gratitude that can coincide with grieving and lament.

04:49.181 --> 04:52.786
It's the kind of gratitude that gets us through difficult times.

04:53.474 --> 04:54.055
But here's the thing.

04:55.216 --> 04:57.820
I can't tell you to feel grateful.

04:58.240 --> 04:58.761
It doesn't work.

04:59.502 --> 05:00.483
Let's try, ready?

05:00.523 --> 05:01.645
Be grateful.

05:02.586 --> 05:03.487
See, it didn't work.

05:03.527 --> 05:04.449
It didn't do it, right?

05:04.489 --> 05:08.114
That's because you can't manufacture gratitude.

05:08.614 --> 05:10.677
What you have to do is cultivate it.

05:11.758 --> 05:14.202
And so what can we do to cultivate gratitude?

05:15.023 --> 05:19.869
Well, there are three ways that I want to teach you based off of this passage in Philippians 1.

05:20.009 --> 05:22.292
Three ways to cultivate gratitude.

05:22.333 --> 05:23.474
And the first is this.

05:23.618 --> 05:25.921
Remember what God has done.

05:25.961 --> 05:29.927
All right, look at verse three, how he starts off here.

05:29.967 --> 05:35.696
And he says, I thank my God in all my remembrance of you.

05:35.736 --> 05:39.622
Remembrance cultivates gratitude.

05:40.804 --> 05:45.170
I certainly experienced this last week, last Sunday,

05:45.346 --> 05:51.296
I watched The Last Dance, the documentary that came out about the Chicago Bulls and Michael Jordan.

05:51.537 --> 05:53.881
And man, it was just bringing back all the memories.

05:53.941 --> 06:00.592
It was like reliving my childhood with my children, walking along with it and watching along with it.

06:00.712 --> 06:03.517
And it just brought back all these memories for me.

06:03.557 --> 06:11.250
I thought about my dad taking my brother and I to see Michael Jordan play against the Seattle SuperSonics.

06:11.362 --> 06:12.023
1992.

06:12.203 --> 06:16.890
I thought about getting my first pair of Jordans in 93.

06:16.930 --> 06:20.695
They were the threes, black, red with the cement gray.

06:21.356 --> 06:28.967
I remembered the friends that I was with in 98 when Jordan hit the shot against the Utah Jazz.

06:29.468 --> 06:33.173
See, my remembrance just stirred up gratitude.

06:33.193 --> 06:34.635
I was overwhelmed with it.

06:35.396 --> 06:37.900
And that's exactly what's happening with the Apostle Paul.

06:38.320 --> 06:39.602
He's thinking back.

06:39.970 --> 06:45.098
He's remembering these memories with the church in Philippi.

06:45.138 --> 06:49.546
He's thinking back to the start of the church, what we learned about last week in Acts 16.

06:49.646 --> 06:54.414
Remember, you had this mob beating and then an earthquake and then a jailbreak.

06:54.494 --> 06:55.996
And what comes out of all of that?

06:56.196 --> 06:57.218
A church plant, of course.

06:57.799 --> 06:58.680
He's remembering that.

06:58.701 --> 07:04.530
He's remembering the people, Lydia, the jailer, and his family, the little girl.

07:05.026 --> 07:12.935
He remembers them and this remembrance cultivates gratitude and then that gratitude produces joy.

07:12.995 --> 07:14.637
Let's keep going in the passage.

07:14.657 --> 07:16.039
Let me start at verse three again.

07:16.079 --> 07:32.178
He says, I thank my God and all my remembrance of you always in every prayer of mine for you all, making my prayer with joy because of your partnership in the gospel from the first day until now, joy.

07:32.834 --> 07:39.044
This is the first of a dozen times that Paul mentions joy in this letter to the Philippians.

07:39.585 --> 07:48.799
And every time that note is sounded, it's going to build into an orchestra of deep, lasting, beautiful joy.

07:49.821 --> 07:54.047
But see, joy, what we're seeing here, flows from gratitude.

07:54.068 --> 07:55.390
I just think about it.

07:55.910 --> 07:58.194
Grateful people are joyful people.

07:58.818 --> 08:04.508
And that kind of joy and gratitude is not dependent on external circumstances.

08:05.510 --> 08:08.555
You see, joy is not the absence of trials.

08:09.217 --> 08:12.823
It's the life-giving presence of God in the midst of trials.

08:14.085 --> 08:17.912
And throughout Philippians, we're learning about defiant joy.

08:18.613 --> 08:23.442
Yeah, this is a difficult time, but there's still so much to be grateful for.

08:24.226 --> 08:29.471
So I want to challenge you, don't let all the changes blind you to what is unchanging.

08:30.272 --> 08:33.715
Don't let the losses rob you of all that you still have.

08:34.336 --> 08:39.001
Don't let the need to lament make you think that there's not need to also give thanks.

08:40.462 --> 08:46.348
See, it would be easy to think that lament and giving thanks are opposites.

08:46.949 --> 08:48.210
You can't do both of them.

08:48.270 --> 08:52.274
Like if I'm going to lament, how could I ever give thanks or vice versa?

08:52.354 --> 08:55.678
I would say that gratitude and lament are not contradictory.

08:56.459 --> 08:59.323
In fact, I would say that there are two sides of the same coin.

08:59.583 --> 09:02.167
We've learned this during this season more than ever.

09:02.687 --> 09:08.415
Loss actually helps us to be grateful for things that we used to take for granted.

09:08.475 --> 09:11.779
Think about that in our lives right now.

09:11.819 --> 09:20.530
May we never take for granted again, being able to gather together in person as the church.

09:21.346 --> 09:22.387
and exalt Christ.

09:23.148 --> 09:28.134
May we never take for granted hearing the voices of others saying as we sing.

09:28.214 --> 09:35.682
May we never take for granted being able to go and sit next to a friend who's hurting and just be with them.

09:36.543 --> 09:44.332
May we never take for granted a handshake, a hug, being near to people that we love.

09:45.533 --> 09:50.098
This is something that I hope that we learn through this time as we lament

09:50.434 --> 09:56.101
that our gratitude actually grows for things that maybe we once took for granted.

09:56.121 --> 10:05.032
And that actually stirs up in us a desire, looking forward to being able to experience those things once again.

10:05.072 --> 10:11.821
And so I would encourage you to lament in this time, but also to give thanks to the Lord.

10:11.901 --> 10:15.265
There's so much to be thankful for in all of this.

10:16.046 --> 10:19.090
And so whatever comes your way, you really have two options.

10:19.714 --> 10:24.920
You can either take things for granted or receive them with gratitude.

10:25.881 --> 10:33.851
And so let this be a time where we learn not to take things for granted, but to receive them with gratitude and to do so in every circumstance.

10:33.871 --> 10:39.258
1 Thessalonians 5, 18 says, give thanks in all circumstances.

10:40.139 --> 10:43.303
Now it doesn't say give thanks for all circumstances.

10:43.923 --> 10:46.566
It says give thanks in all circumstances.

10:46.627 --> 10:46.887
Why?

10:47.428 --> 10:49.490
Because we know that God is with us in them.

10:49.762 --> 10:51.324
He's with us in those circumstances.

10:52.085 --> 10:53.887
Let's keep going in Philippians one.

10:53.907 --> 10:55.208
Look at verse six.

10:55.228 --> 10:57.290
This is one of my favorite verses in the whole Bible.

10:58.231 --> 11:01.675
Paul says, and I am sure of this with all the uncertainty.

11:01.835 --> 11:09.504
I am sure of this that he who began a good work in you will bring it to completion at the day of Jesus Christ.

11:10.265 --> 11:12.047
And so he's remembering.

11:12.087 --> 11:18.674
And now we see that looking back on God's faithfulness is giving him confidence for moving forward.

11:19.234 --> 11:21.077
And the point that he's making here is simple.

11:21.738 --> 11:23.180
God finishes what he starts.

11:24.362 --> 11:30.011
He doesn't just start a work of grace and then leave it to you to finish through your effort.

11:30.732 --> 11:35.138
No, the Lord saves and he sustains what he starts.

11:35.779 --> 11:36.360
He finishes.

11:37.682 --> 11:42.770
This reminds me of plans that someone had in Chicago years ago.

11:42.790 --> 11:47.858
They were going to build a building that was going to be called the Chicago Spire.

11:48.386 --> 11:51.669
This building would be 150 stories tall.

11:52.090 --> 11:55.393
It was going to be the tallest building in the Western Hemisphere.

11:55.953 --> 11:57.275
The plans started in 2005.

11:57.835 --> 12:02.300
They broke ground in 2007, and they built a foundation.

12:02.360 --> 12:06.444
I mean, this is one of the biggest, strongest foundations ever built.

12:07.425 --> 12:08.626
And that was in 2007.

12:08.646 --> 12:13.931
And then of course, in 2008, you had the financial recession that came into play.

12:13.991 --> 12:17.074
Everything got put on hold on that.

12:17.346 --> 12:23.135
And to this day, the foundation is still sitting there in Chicago, in the heart of Chicago.

12:23.756 --> 12:25.739
See, they never built on it.

12:26.320 --> 12:27.481
They had a great idea.

12:27.521 --> 12:29.565
They got off to a great start.

12:29.685 --> 12:33.691
It was a good work, but the builders couldn't finish what they started.

12:34.472 --> 12:35.413
God's not like that.

12:36.115 --> 12:39.440
God always finishes what he starts.

12:39.460 --> 12:46.290
And some of you especially need to hear that today because you can look back and see that God's done a great work in your life in the past.

12:46.978 --> 12:49.421
But right now you look at your life and you think, I'm not sure.

12:49.902 --> 12:50.924
Can I get through this?

12:51.484 --> 12:52.346
Can I hold on?

12:52.806 --> 12:54.308
Can I endure in all of this?

12:54.328 --> 12:58.474
I want you to hear God can get you through this.

12:59.796 --> 13:02.720
Christian, God will get you through this.

13:03.301 --> 13:03.562
Why?

13:03.602 --> 13:05.905
Because God finishes what he starts.

13:07.467 --> 13:10.111
And so this is a time where we need to cultivate gratitude.

13:10.171 --> 13:10.732
How do we do that?

13:10.772 --> 13:13.255
First, we remember what God has done.

13:14.177 --> 13:15.058
But second,

13:15.426 --> 13:17.709
We trust in what God is doing.

13:18.070 --> 13:23.797
We shift here from the past to the present and look at verses seven and eight in Philippians one.

13:24.498 --> 13:30.427
Paul goes on and he says in verse seven, it is right for me to feel this way about you all because I hold you in my heart.

13:31.188 --> 13:38.157
For you are all partakers with me of grace, both in my imprisonment and in the defense and confirmation of the gospel.

13:38.698 --> 13:39.739
For God is my witness.

13:40.260 --> 13:44.626
How I yearn for you with all, with the affection of Christ,

13:44.770 --> 13:45.411
Jesus.

13:46.392 --> 13:51.216
Now, I want you to notice here the present tense of the verbs that he's using.

13:51.937 --> 13:55.080
I hold you in my heart, not I held you in my heart.

13:55.681 --> 13:59.144
He says, you are all partakers with me of grace.

13:59.164 --> 14:02.287
He doesn't say you were partakers of grace with me.

14:03.128 --> 14:03.908
And think about this.

14:04.649 --> 14:05.650
Paul's in prison.

14:05.710 --> 14:13.778
There's literally a wall between him and the church of Philippians, let alone hundreds of miles, right?

14:14.338 --> 14:21.388
And so here he is in prison, probably in isolation, other than guards that are around him.

14:21.448 --> 14:24.072
And he's saying, I hold you in my heart.

14:25.094 --> 14:27.778
Now, this doesn't seem to make sense.

14:27.818 --> 14:30.842
I mean, it's either crazy or it's beautiful.

14:31.764 --> 14:35.309
But I would say that this is one of the most striking features of the book of Philippians.

14:36.170 --> 14:41.638
Paul is in prison, and yet he rejoices repeatedly in the gift of community.

14:43.200 --> 14:44.242
And I want you to see

14:44.738 --> 14:47.743
especially hear how this is connected to gratitude.

14:48.585 --> 14:55.136
Because we often think of gratitude as an individual thing, something that I need in my heart.

14:55.156 --> 15:00.665
But Philippians is showing us that gratitude is deeply tied to relationships.

15:01.807 --> 15:06.716
Back in verse five that we read earlier, Paul used this beautiful phrase to describe this.

15:07.237 --> 15:10.322
He said that they have a partnership in the gospel.

15:11.106 --> 15:12.408
partnership in the gospel.

15:12.828 --> 15:14.431
This word partnership is really rich.

15:14.471 --> 15:16.754
Paul uses it over and over and over again in Philippians.

15:16.794 --> 15:22.142
It gets translated in different ways, but it means that they share in something in common.

15:22.783 --> 15:24.185
They're bound together.

15:25.607 --> 15:34.319
They have this mutuality, but the center of their relationship, the center of this partnership is not preference or affinity or ethnicity.

15:34.640 --> 15:35.962
No, it's the gospel.

15:37.003 --> 15:38.866
This is a partnership in the gospel.

15:39.522 --> 15:42.425
And a partnership in the gospel is deep.

15:42.745 --> 15:44.347
And there's several different layers to this.

15:44.407 --> 15:47.410
First of all, a partnership in the gospel is spiritual.

15:48.532 --> 15:50.574
We know that they are united in Christ.

15:51.174 --> 15:54.959
We learn in Philippians two that they share a partnership in the Holy Spirit.

15:55.699 --> 16:00.444
In chapter three, it says that they share in the sufferings of Christ.

16:01.285 --> 16:05.810
So this partnership in the gospel is spiritual, but it's also relational.

16:06.511 --> 16:08.053
It's deeply relational.

16:08.073 --> 16:09.394
We learn from this letter that

16:09.570 --> 16:13.957
The Philippian church sent a man named Epaphroditus to Paul to help him out.

16:14.458 --> 16:16.942
Paul then here is writing a letter back to them.

16:17.262 --> 16:19.806
It's incredibly relational, this partnership that they have.

16:20.487 --> 16:22.851
But then third, it's also financial.

16:23.912 --> 16:25.815
They are supporting him financially.

16:25.896 --> 16:28.880
I mean, turn in your Bible to Philippians chapter four.

16:28.940 --> 16:32.466
And let me read to you verses 15 and 16.

16:33.888 --> 16:36.512
He said, well, actually, yeah, start in verse 14.

16:37.113 --> 16:37.714
He says,

16:38.050 --> 16:40.532
Yet it was kind of you to share my trouble.

16:40.572 --> 16:43.355
That word share there is the same word with partnership.

16:44.356 --> 16:59.010
He says, it was kind of you to share my trouble and you Philippians yourselves know that in the beginning of the gospel, when I left Macedonia, no church entered into partnership with me in giving and receiving except you only.

17:00.131 --> 17:07.698
So the church in Philippi was supporting Paul financially in his missionary journeys.

17:08.706 --> 17:16.575
And so they have this gospel partnership that is deeply spiritual and yet plays out in the most practical ways.

17:17.796 --> 17:20.900
Now again, I want you to see how all this is connected to gratitude.

17:21.901 --> 17:26.446
David Brooks gives some good language for this and an article that he wrote for the New York Times.

17:27.227 --> 17:30.551
He said that gratitude is a form of social glue.

17:30.571 --> 17:31.472
I love that.

17:32.113 --> 17:36.498
And according to Brooks, gratitude, and I quote him here, gratitude,

17:36.578 --> 17:50.500
reminds us that a society isn't just a contract based on mutual benefit, but an organic connection based on natural sympathy, connections that are nurtured, not by self-interest, but by loyalty and service.

17:51.701 --> 18:02.418
So in other words, when one person is grateful, it actually evokes gratefulness in others, which then creates a culture of gratitude in the community at large.

18:03.394 --> 18:06.879
So I want to call you to give thanks for the relationships that you have.

18:07.941 --> 18:14.050
Don't let the distance keep you from growing in depth with brothers and sisters in Christ.

18:14.771 --> 18:21.300
Be deliberate about investing in friendships and staying connected to the church, especially in this time.

18:22.802 --> 18:26.388
So to cultivate gratitude, we've got to remember what God has done.

18:26.408 --> 18:29.272
We've got to trust in what God is doing.

18:29.312 --> 18:30.674
And then third,

18:30.850 --> 18:33.273
We've got a hope in what God will do.

18:34.054 --> 18:39.521
Let me read to you verses nine through 11 of Philippians 1.

18:39.801 --> 19:00.306
The Apostle Paul says, and it is my prayer that your love may abound more and more with knowledge and all discernment so that you may approve what is excellent and so be pure and blameless for the day of Christ filled with the fruit of righteousness that comes through Jesus Christ to the glory and praise of God.

19:01.858 --> 19:07.988
It's as if Paul is saying, imagine the possibilities of what God can do in the midst of this.

19:08.989 --> 19:11.273
And he expresses this through prayer.

19:12.855 --> 19:25.055
I would say that prayer is the purest form of gratitude, because every gift is from above, from our father who loves to give gifts to his children.

19:25.115 --> 19:26.697
Think about it like this.

19:26.717 --> 19:29.682
There is nothing good in your life.

19:30.178 --> 19:32.000
that you can't trace back to God.

19:33.422 --> 19:33.843
Nothing.

19:34.844 --> 19:39.150
Every good and perfect gift comes from above.

19:40.212 --> 19:46.460
And so our natural response to that is to give thanks, to express gratitude.

19:47.702 --> 19:49.604
I mean, think about it like this.

19:50.486 --> 19:52.589
What if someone made you an incredible meal?

19:53.430 --> 19:56.594
Your favorite food, favorite drink,

19:57.058 --> 20:04.247
they did all the work and they made you this meal and you sit at the table and they come and they bring you this meal and put it right before you and you get to eat it.

20:04.667 --> 20:05.569
What if they did that?

20:06.169 --> 20:12.237
And you just kind of like looked at them and kind of like shrugged and just like dug in and started eating.

20:13.098 --> 20:14.379
No, you would never do that, right?

20:14.419 --> 20:21.228
Like if if someone went through all this and gave you this incredible meal, you would give thanks for that, right?

20:21.889 --> 20:22.930
Well, scripture says that

20:23.042 --> 20:25.184
It's God who ultimately feeds us.

20:25.304 --> 20:28.387
It's God who ultimately provides for our needs.

20:28.467 --> 20:30.429
So maybe we give thanks.

20:30.510 --> 20:32.612
I mean, literally even just eating food.

20:32.692 --> 20:38.357
We have a chance several times a day, maybe more now during quarantine times than ever.

20:38.938 --> 20:47.166
We have lots of chances when we eat to be able to just pause beforehand and give thanks and to recognize that all we have comes from the Lord.

20:47.226 --> 20:50.930
Think about it like this.

20:51.426 --> 20:55.710
What if we were up in the air, whether you'd be able to breathe today or tomorrow?

20:56.471 --> 21:01.516
And someone came to you and they had a way to actually put air in your lungs.

21:02.216 --> 21:06.681
You would use that air in your lungs to give thanks, to express gratitude.

21:07.641 --> 21:11.025
Well, listen, God's the one who has put air in your lungs today.

21:11.085 --> 21:12.706
He is the giver of life.

21:12.786 --> 21:14.989
He is the giver of every gift that we have.

21:15.549 --> 21:18.652
And so may we give thanks for everything that he's given us.

21:19.733 --> 21:20.754
And we give thanks

21:20.866 --> 21:21.387
through prayer.

21:21.727 --> 21:29.454
Prayer is an expression of gratitude, but it's also an instrument to cultivate more gratitude in our lives.

21:30.075 --> 21:32.798
So I want to encourage you to be disciplined in prayer.

21:32.838 --> 21:38.944
And as we look in Philippians one, what does Paul pray for the church in Philippi?

21:39.444 --> 21:42.107
Well, he prays that their love would abound.

21:43.388 --> 21:49.394
Let's see, for the people of God, we're not driven by self-preservation, but by self-giving love.

21:50.146 --> 21:54.553
And God doesn't want us just to experience just enough love.

21:55.234 --> 22:03.946
No, he wants us to abound in love, knowing that God is abounding in love for us so that we can be abounding in love for one another and for our city.

22:04.908 --> 22:09.915
But then he goes on to say that love must be accompanied with knowledge and discernment.

22:09.975 --> 22:11.377
This is such an important word.

22:12.018 --> 22:15.924
During this pandemic, our passion must be coupled with wisdom.

22:17.166 --> 22:19.890
We need to follow government guidelines for public health,

22:20.322 --> 22:25.009
And yet we need to find creative ways to serve one another and to show love to our city.

22:26.651 --> 22:32.300
And so we can have hope in the midst of this pandemic because we know God's promises.

22:33.201 --> 22:34.863
We know that our future is guaranteed.

22:34.944 --> 22:37.387
We know that he will not forsake us.

22:37.968 --> 22:41.553
We know that he is working all things together for the good of those who love him.

22:42.014 --> 22:47.422
We know that he is bringing peace even now in the midst of chaos.

22:47.442 --> 22:50.226
And so church, I just want to remind you,

22:50.882 --> 22:53.826
In all of this, we're going to get through this together.

22:55.227 --> 22:56.609
And I'm not saying it will be easy.

22:56.629 --> 23:02.136
I'm certainly not saying it will be quick, but we are going to get through this together.

23:02.176 --> 23:09.745
And saying that certainly doesn't diminish the hardship that we're all experiencing right now.

23:09.785 --> 23:15.852
And as I said before, expressing gratitude doesn't keep us from grieving as well.

23:16.874 --> 23:19.136
I've grieved deeply this week.

23:19.397 --> 23:20.498
This was a hard week.

23:21.122 --> 23:25.326
I heard of several new people in our church who now have COVID-19.

23:26.447 --> 23:32.153
I heard of several people in our church who have had family members who passed away this week.

23:32.173 --> 23:37.058
I heard of many people in our church this last week who lost their jobs.

23:38.780 --> 23:39.480
I grieved.

23:40.341 --> 23:42.403
We're all grieving in one way or another.

23:43.104 --> 23:45.046
We got to take that to the Lord and lament.

23:45.847 --> 23:49.170
And yet even in grieving, we can be grateful.

23:50.210 --> 23:56.678
And even as I've grieved, I can say that, but I'm grateful because what we have in Christ cannot be taken from us.

23:58.180 --> 24:05.929
We can be grateful that in trials that we've got one another, we can be grateful knowing that God is bringing beauty out of this brokenness.

24:07.331 --> 24:11.135
See, Paul says, I give thanks to God when I remember you and pray for you.

24:11.976 --> 24:16.882
And as I read that this week and prepared to preach,

24:18.242 --> 24:20.785
It welled up joy and gratitude in my heart for you.

24:21.565 --> 24:27.331
See, I'm certainly not the apostle Paul, but he's writing this letter to the church that he'd planted.

24:27.471 --> 24:31.335
And I can't read this without feeling the same way towards you all.

24:32.276 --> 24:33.658
I pray for you every day.

24:33.678 --> 24:36.841
Our other elders, we are praying for you constantly.

24:36.901 --> 24:42.287
And as we do, we are filled with gratitude and joy, especially now.

24:43.027 --> 24:45.650
I mean, this time it's been a test for us.

24:45.890 --> 24:50.655
It certainly is a test of faith for all of us as individuals, but for us as a church as well.

24:51.436 --> 24:54.379
In church, you've been so faithful through this.

24:55.320 --> 25:02.668
We've had to make quick decisions and communicate things really quickly in much less time than we normally would.

25:02.688 --> 25:05.671
And you followed direction.

25:06.352 --> 25:08.955
You've responded to leadership.

25:09.455 --> 25:11.858
Community groups are rallying together.

25:12.162 --> 25:17.988
You've continued to give faithfully to the church so that we can be generous to those in the church and to our city.

25:18.028 --> 25:20.350
You've been praying throughout this time.

25:20.370 --> 25:27.557
I'm just overwhelmed with gratitude and joy as I reflect on you all during this time.

25:27.637 --> 25:30.660
I can identify with the Apostle Paul in that.

25:31.881 --> 25:39.108
Now, I started telling you that I can't tell you to be grateful or to feel grateful.

25:39.148 --> 25:41.650
We have to cultivate gratitude, but

25:42.274 --> 25:52.049
I want to close by giving you a practical challenge in a gospel declaration that I believe will cultivate deeper gratitude in our lives.

25:52.750 --> 25:55.054
And so the practical challenge is this.

25:55.094 --> 26:05.810
I would love for you to take some time this week and sit down with a piece of paper, maybe with a journal, and write down things that you're grateful for.

26:06.370 --> 26:17.582
And I would encourage you to do this even in the way that we've seen the Apostle Paul expressing gratitude where he's looking back into the past, he's giving thanks in the present, he's looking forward into the future.

26:17.622 --> 26:24.029
Take a few minutes and write down all the things from your past that you're grateful for.

26:24.069 --> 26:30.076
And then take a few minutes and write down things that you're grateful for right now in the present.

26:30.837 --> 26:32.178
And then take a few minutes

26:32.354 --> 26:37.439
and write down things that you're grateful for in the future, things that you're looking forward to.

26:37.480 --> 26:45.969
I did this earlier this week personally and honestly it just cultivated so much more gratitude in my heart.

26:46.990 --> 26:53.136
And then there's one more step with this challenge that I want you to do after you express gratitude in that way.

26:53.156 --> 26:58.322
I want you to be deliberate about telling people in your life that you're grateful for them.

26:59.138 --> 27:07.029
call people, send text messages, set up Zoom calls, emails, whatever it is, and just let people know that you're grateful.

27:07.069 --> 27:12.556
Don't let another day go by without telling people in your life that you are thankful for them.

27:13.277 --> 27:14.719
So that's the practical challenge.

27:14.779 --> 27:23.191
But I want to end with this gospel declaration because when we talk about all the things that we can be grateful for, there's so much that will come to mind.

27:23.231 --> 27:28.658
And as you write those things down, you'll be grateful for friends and provision

27:28.802 --> 27:32.726
Even I'm grateful that this is a time where a world is slowing down.

27:32.766 --> 27:34.849
There's so much to be grateful for.

27:35.369 --> 27:38.653
But here's the greatest thing to be grateful for.

27:38.673 --> 27:40.195
And nothing compares to it.

27:41.096 --> 27:44.920
The king of the universe loves you and has sought you out.

27:45.701 --> 27:53.129
And even though you've sinned and rebelled against him, he is for you and he sent his son for you.

27:54.111 --> 27:57.234
And his son, Jesus Christ, lived a perfect life.

27:57.922 --> 28:01.787
Every area of our lives where we fell short, he's faithful.

28:02.868 --> 28:08.175
Everything he did was perfectly loving to the Father and to neighbor and to the world.

28:08.535 --> 28:15.524
He lived a perfect life and yet he took that perfect life and offered it up as a sacrifice in our place.

28:16.485 --> 28:27.218
See, we have sinned and fallen short of the glory of God, but Jesus goes to the cross to die for our sins so that we can be forgiven, washed clean,

28:27.522 --> 28:31.787
made new, reconciled to God so that we can have a relationship with him.

28:32.248 --> 28:33.429
And then he rose from the grave.

28:34.230 --> 28:35.091
He's alive today.

28:35.232 --> 28:41.059
And the same power that rose Jesus from the grave can dwell in us through faith.

28:42.040 --> 28:56.338
And when we trust in Christ, when we believe in the gospel, this good news that Christ has died for our sins, rose from the grave to bring us into the kingdom of God, then we can see the immeasurable riches of God's grace that we have in Christ.

28:56.866 --> 29:01.112
We have more to be grateful for than we could ever imagine.

29:01.974 --> 29:02.855
So let me ask you this.

29:02.895 --> 29:07.081
Do you see God's grace, God's abounding grace in your life?

29:07.882 --> 29:09.184
If you do, then give thanks.

29:10.166 --> 29:15.974
Express your gratitude and prayer and worship and then a life lived for the glory of God.

29:17.957 --> 29:22.284
How can we be a people of gratitude in a time of difficulty?

29:22.644 --> 29:23.826
That's what we've been talking about.

29:24.226 --> 29:31.834
And we've seen in Philippians that we've got to remember what God has done, trust in what God is doing and hope in what God will do.

29:32.935 --> 29:43.326
And then we can say with the Apostle Paul, I am sure of this, that he who began a good work will bring it to completion at the day of Jesus Christ.

29:43.907 --> 29:46.570
And for that, we will be forever grateful.

29:47.151 --> 29:47.831
Let's pray together.

29:49.974 --> 29:54.098
God, we thank you for your grace and we respond

29:54.434 --> 29:55.375
with gratitude.

29:57.419 --> 29:58.340
We give you glory.

29:59.061 --> 30:00.103
We give you all the credit.

30:00.543 --> 30:01.685
We give you all the praise.

30:03.227 --> 30:10.859
Lord, we ask that you would give us eyes to see how gracious you've been to us, all the gifts that you've given us.

30:12.001 --> 30:23.378
But Lord, help us then by your spirit to not rejoice merely in the gifts, but to look to the giver of the gifts and to rejoice in you, our Savior.

30:23.586 --> 30:25.970
We pray this in Jesus name, amen.

